Valgrind reports use-after-free as "Invalid read" or "Invalid write" with a note: "Address is 0 bytes inside a block of size N free'd".
The stack trace shows two locations: where the bad access happened, and where the memory was originally freed.
Without Valgrind, the freed memory often still contains the old data — the bug appears harmless. The allocator just marks it reusable.
In exploitation, use-after-free means controlling what gets allocated in that freed slot next — making the "harmless" bug into arbitrary code execution.
